(21,	14,	'Swing Trading Strategy 2',	'<h3>There are many different strategies on how to approach swing trading a stock market trend.&nbsp; Everyone has a different risk thresh hold and has a different personality.&nbsp; That will determine which strategy makes you feel comfortable.&nbsp; You have to feel comfortable with your trading system because you have to be able to implement your strategy over and over without hesitation.&nbsp; However you always want to be trading with a stop loss and target which you should know before you enter any trade or position.&nbsp; You should never enter a trade then be figuring out when you&#39;re going to exit.&nbsp; Another way of trading this uptrend is after you draw your trendlines, like the ones on the image, you want to be buying the pullbacks as close to the support trendline as possible.&nbsp; The support trendline is the line at the bottom of the trend.&nbsp; When the stock pullback to the support trend line you would be entering the market with a stop loss below the previous swing low.&nbsp; Your target or exit should be when the trend is broken or a predetermined resistance level.&nbsp; For example a good entry point for this stock would be the pull back at the 140 level.&nbsp; The stock trended upward from that level all the way up to 240 level where it started moving sideways.&nbsp; Practice. Practice. Practice.</h3>',	'assets/uploads/users/Downtrend_Channel1.PNG',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-27 13:37:20',	'2019-07-27 13:37:20',	''),
(20,	14,	'Swing Trading Strategy 1',	'<h3>There are many different strategies to employ when trading short term.&nbsp; In this course we will look at a few strategies that are the most profitable for us at Relentless Trade.&nbsp; These strategies will be for traders and investors that are working 9 to 5 jobs and or busy doing the day where the market cant be watched all day and everyday. One of the simplest strategies is known as Swing Trading.&nbsp; Swing Trading is identifying an uptrend (higher highs and higher lows) and buying if the stock trades higher than the pullback&rsquo;s previous day&rsquo;s high.&nbsp; So when you see the stock move higher then the previous swing high you would generally buy the stock and hold as long as it doesn&#39;t trade below the previous swing low or exit on a predetermined resistance level.&nbsp;</h3>',	'assets/uploads/users/Swing_Trade_nvda.PNG',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-27 13:27:13',	'2019-07-27 13:27:13',	''),
(31,	14,	'Swing Trading Strategy 1',	'<h3>When you identify a downtrend (lower lows and lower highs) you want to sell or short stock when it trades below the previous swing low and exit trade when the stock breaks back above the previous swing high or the stock hits a predetermined support level.</h3>',	'assets/uploads/users/Downtrend_Swing_Trade1.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 13:14:19',	'2019-08-20 13:14:19',	''),
(32,	14,	'Swing Trading Strategy 2',	'<h3>Trading the pullback on the downtrend is similar to trading it when its trending upward just in reverse.&nbsp; When the stock pullback to the resistance trend line you want to enter the stock by selling.&nbsp; The resistance trendline is the line above the trend.&nbsp; That acts as an area where sellers are looking to short stock.&nbsp; Your stop loss should be above the prior swing high.&nbsp; Your target should be a support level that previous buyers in the past bought the market sending the market in the opposite direction or you should be exiting the market when the trend is broken and the previous swing high was breached. Example: Entry-$3.98 Exit-$2.81</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>$3.98 was the 1st major pullback.&nbsp; The market went lower from there to $2.80.&nbsp; As you can see there where several touches at the $2.80 level where that horizontal line is drawn.&nbsp; &nbsp;The actual support also goes back sometime as well.&nbsp; The stock trended down to that level 2 years ago to that level and the buyers were sitting on that level waiting and they took the market higher.&nbsp; Then last year the same thing the market sold off to that level and buyers bought the market from that level and it trended higher.&nbsp; It takes time to see these things.&nbsp; Practice. Practice, Practice.</h3>',	'assets/uploads/users/Uptrend_Channel_2.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 13:15:55',	'2019-08-20 13:15:55',	''),
(22,	16,	'Stock Option Course.  ',	'<p>A stock option gives a trader and/or investor the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a stock at an agreed upon price and date. There are two types of options: puts, which is a bet that a stock will go down, or calls, which is a bet that a stock will go up.&nbsp; The image above is an option chain.&nbsp; An option chain tells you what is available for each stock if that stock is optionable.&nbsp; If you look at the dates on the left it tells you all the different expiration periods.&nbsp; Stock have either weekly, monthly, quarterly or all the above contracts.&nbsp; In this course we will talk extensively about the important stuff that you need to trade stock options successfully.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1135132251738024_pqX7Pc2Gp1mVnfhvx6tB_height6401.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-10 07:14:39',	'2019-08-10 07:14:39',	''),
(10,	7,	'Charting Course',	'<h3>It will talk a little about combining green and red candles on the chart to form patterns.&nbsp; These patterns will give you an idea of what the market maybe trying to do.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>On the chart, each candlestick includes an open, high, low and close price for the time frame. The trader sets the time frame of each candle. For example, to see the high, low, open and close price over a five-minute period, a trader would set the time frame of the candlestick chart to 5 minutes.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Every five minutes a new candlestick is created, and it takes five minutes to complete before another one begins. Candlesticks also show the current price, whether the price moved up or down over the time frame, and the price range the asset covered in that time.</h3>',	'assets/uploads/users/Candlestick-Components-Max-450W1.jpg',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-06-29 11:38:47',	'2019-06-29 11:38:47',	''),
(27,	7,	'Charting Course',	'<h3>This picture shows the market moving upwards looking at the first 6 candles which means buyers are controlling the market then on the 7th candlestick which appears red the sellers are starting to control the market and take it down</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/images_(2)11.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 13:06:42',	'2019-08-20 13:06:42',	''),
(28,	7,	'Charting Course',	'<h3>This chart shows the market moving down in the first 4 bars then buyers are starting to control the market starting from the 5th bar.&nbsp; The more charts you look at the more you will understand and start to get a feel for how the market moves.</h3>',	'assets/uploads/users/candlesticks-1-56a22da33df78cf77272e55111.jpg',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 13:07:52',	'2019-08-20 13:07:52',	''),
(8,	7,	'Green Candlestick',	'<h3>Green Candlestick represents up period in the market.&nbsp; Each candle may have a different length of body and wick depending on open and close of the market.&nbsp; The wick is known as the vertical line at the top and/or bottom of the body.</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/typical_candle_040607_(1).jpg',	'assets/uploads/video/AAPL_-_Charts_-_86_____74_Main@thinkorswim_build_1958_2019-09-25_19-27-542.mp4',	'2019-06-29 11:27:33',	'2019-10-27 02:09:39',	'assets/uploads/video/AAPL_-_Charts_-_86_____74_Main@thinkorswim_build_1958_2019-09-25_19-27-543.mp4'),
(30,	7,	'Green Candlestick',	'<h3>The wick on the top of the candle tells you the high price of that candle which is called upper shadow.&nbsp; The wick on the bottom of the candle tells you the low of that candle which is called the lower shadow.</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Candlestick_Slideshow-625x420-021_(1).png',	'assets/uploads/video/AAPL_-_Charts_-_86_____74_Main@thinkorswim_build_1958_2019-09-25_19-27-54.mp4',	'2019-08-20 13:11:09',	'2019-10-27 02:04:55',	'assets/uploads/video/AAPL_-_Charts_-_86_____74_Main@thinkorswim_build_1958_2019-09-25_19-27-541.mp4'),
(9,	7,	'Red Candlesticks.',	'<h3>The red candlestick represents down period in the market. Each candle may have a different length of body and wick depending on open and close of the market.&nbsp; The wick is known as the vertical line at the top and/or bottom of the body.&nbsp;&nbsp;</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Red20Candle20copy-5bfd6a12c9e77c0051d3ec0a2.gif',	'assets/uploads/video/GOOG_-_Charts_-_86_____74_Main@thinkorswim_build_1958_2019-09-29_17-24-54.mp4',	'2019-06-29 11:31:50',	'2019-10-27 02:13:45',	'assets/uploads/video/GOOG_-_Charts_-_86_____74_Main@thinkorswim_build_1958_2019-09-29_17-24-541.mp4'),
(29,	7,	'Red Candlesticks.',	'<h3>The wick on the top of the candle tells you the high price of that candle which is called upper shadow.&nbsp; The wick on the bottom of the candle tells you the low of that candle which is called the lower shadow.</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/images11.jpg',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 13:09:30',	'2019-08-20 13:09:30',	''),
(13,	8,	'Charting Course',	'<h3>Learning and Recognizing support and resistance is very important in trading.&amp;nbsp; The concepts of support and resistance are undoubtedly two of the most highly discussed attributes of technical analysis. Part of analyzing chart patterns, these terms are used by traders to refer to price levels on charts that tend to act as barriers, preventing the price of an asset from getting pushed in a certain direction</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/support_resistance_241.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-13 09:25:57',	'2019-07-13 09:25:57',	''),
(14,	8,	'Support (Demand Zone)',	'<h3>Support (Demand Zone) is the area where a lot of resting bids (buy orders) are in the market.&amp;nbsp; Bids is the price that the buyer is willing to pay.&amp;nbsp; It is the level that traders are looking to buy keeping the market from going lower.&amp;nbsp; You should see several touches at a certain price or area without significantly going below that zone to be considered strong support or demand.&amp;nbsp; When price hits support there is a higher probability the price will get thrown back in opposite direction,&amp;nbsp; When price goes below or breaks through support to the downside that old support now turns in to what is called resistance.</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/newimage.gif',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-13 09:26:36',	'2019-07-13 09:26:36',	''),
(15,	8,	'Resistance (Supply Zone)',	'<h3>Resistance (Supply Zone) is the area where a lot of resting offers (sell orders) are in the market.&nbsp; Offers is the price that the Seller is willing to pay.&nbsp; It is the level that traders are looking to sell keeping the market from going higher.&nbsp; You should see several touches at a certain price or area without significantly going above that zone to be considered strong resistance or supply.&nbsp; When price hits resistance there is a higher probability the price will get thrown back in opposite direction,&nbsp; When price goes above or breaks through resistance to the upside that old resistance now turns in to what is called support.&nbsp; See 1C</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1130038201591605_M93l8zfprFNp9zW9qKcH_height640.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-13 09:28:13',	'2019-07-13 09:28:13',	''),
(16,	8,	'Support and Resistance',	'<h3>Support and Resistance can be horizontal or it can move diagonally going up or down.&nbsp; If you see each successive peak and trough higher than the ones found before it that is called an uptrend.&nbsp; An uptrend provides investors with an opportunity to profit from prices moving higher. Selling a stock once it has failed to create a higher peak and trough is one of the most effective ways to avoid large losses that can result from a change in trend. In the picture you see lines drawn above the higher highs and below the higher lows.&nbsp; Some technical traders utilize trendlines to identify an uptrend and spot possible trend reversals. The trendline is drawn along the rising swing lows, which helps show where future swing lows may form.&nbsp; See 1F</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1130038201591607_y49cS8e29ih5ODiiJXrW_height6401.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-13 09:29:49',	'2019-07-13 09:29:49',	''),
(17,	8,	'stock trending upward',	'<h3>This is another image of a stock trending upward.&nbsp; There is a support line drawn at the base of the up trend where you see each low higher than the one prior.&nbsp; As long as each low is higher than the previous one than that support is still intact.</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1130038201591609_14Zq8LrQYslRTqV9E5FF_height6401.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-13 09:30:30',	'2019-07-13 09:30:30',	''),
(18,	8,	'Downtrend',	'<h3>In this image you see what is called a Downtrend.&nbsp; &nbsp; A downtrend is when the stock is making a lower high and a lower low or If you see each successive peak and trough lower than the ones found before it that is called a downtrend.&nbsp; A downtrend provides investors with an opportunity to profit from prices moving lower.&nbsp; In order to make money in a downtrend your broker will let you borrow that stock from them sell it to another investor and buy the stock back at some point in the future ideally when that downtrend is over.&nbsp; Some technical traders utilize trendlines to identify a downtrend and spot possible trend reversals. The trendline is drawn along the declining swing highs, which helps show where future swing highs may form.&nbsp; See 1E&nbsp;</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1130038201591603_KjgmGwdseGreW4pxyCxg_height6401.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-07-13 09:31:00',	'2019-07-13 09:31:00',	''),
(23,	16,	'Stock Option Course.',	'<h3>A stock option gives a trader and/or investor the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a stock at an agreed upon price and date. There are two types of options: puts, which is a bet that a stock will go down, or calls, which is a bet that a stock will go up. &nbsp;The image above is an option chain. &nbsp;An option chain tells you what is available for each stock if that stock is optionable. &nbsp;If you look at the dates on the left it tells you all the different expiration periods. &nbsp;Stock have either weekly, monthly, quarterly or all the above contracts. &nbsp;In this course we will talk extensively about the important stuff that you need to trade stock options successfully.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://carz91.com/tradeGame/assets/uploads/users/Option_Chain.PNG\" style=\"height:311px; width:991px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This an image of an opened option chain.&nbsp; When you open the option chain you get a lot of valuable information that you need to make decisions according to your trading system and plan.&nbsp; An option chain gives you volume, open interest, the bid/ask spread, and greeks for both calls and puts.&nbsp; Greeks are delta, gamma, theta and vega which we will talk more about as we go through the course.&nbsp; Depending on your brokerage you can customize your option chain to fit your needs and what information you need to make trading decisions.&nbsp; Generally you want to trade options that have some volume and open interest. The more traders in a particular options strike, the better the chances you&rsquo;ll have to get in and out of your trade without too much slippage.&nbsp; There are many different factors that go into option pricing and how it changes over time according to how the security moves.&nbsp; Delta tells you how much the option will move for every point the security moves.&nbsp; For example if the security move up one point the option would appreciate $0.48 on the 128 calls strike price.&nbsp; Gamma tells you how much the delta will change for every one point move of the security.&nbsp; For example when looking at the 128 calls if the security moves up one point gamma will change delta from $0.48 to $0.57.&nbsp; Theta is time decay so for everyday that passes the option will depreciate whatever amount theta states.&nbsp; All options depreciate regardless if it moves or not.&nbsp; The closer the option gets to expiration date the more it decays or depreciates.&nbsp; That&#39;s why the further out in time you purchase the option the more expensive it will be.&nbsp; For example when looking at the 128 calls everyday that passes the option will depreciate -$0.08.&nbsp; Vega tells us how much an option will change for every percentage move in implied volatility.&nbsp; For example if implied volatility goes up by one percent the 128 calls will increase $0.08.&nbsp; Learning to trade options takes time and practice.&nbsp; There are many different option strategies including spreads and straddles that we will go over.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"http://carz91.com/tradeGame/assets/uploads/users/190_Credit_Spread.PNG\" style=\"height:403px; width:432px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many different option strategies to trade depending on what your analysis of the market is.&nbsp; We will go over the essential spreads and strategies to be profitable.&nbsp; We will discuss buying and selling single calls and puts toward the end of the course because it is the simplest and easiest to understand.&nbsp; The first option strategy we will discuss is the vertical spread.&nbsp; There are 2 types of vertical spreads credit spreads and debit spreads. Credit Spreads is selling one option strike price while buying another option strike price.&nbsp; If you&#39;re buying a call you need to be selling a call.&nbsp; If you&#39;re buying a put you should be selling a put to be a credit spread.&nbsp; You&#39;re not buying a call option strike and selling a put option strike.&nbsp; For example if you look at the image of the put option chain you can sell the 190 strike price and buy the 185 strike price.&nbsp; When you do that you will bring in a credit into your account.&nbsp; So if you get filled on the buy order of $2.50 and the sell order of $3.25 you will bring in $0.75 into your account.&nbsp; You generally want to place your orders halfway between the bid and ask price to get the best prices.&nbsp; As long as that stock don&#39;t close below 190 on expiration, which for this option is the third Friday of the month, you will keep the full amount you initially made of $0.75.&nbsp; If it starts to trade below the 190 price you want to close out the trade by buying back the 190 strike you initially sold and selling the 185 you initially bought.&nbsp; To trade a put credit spread you always have to sell the higher strike price and buy the lower strike price,&nbsp; To trade a call credit spread you always have to buy the higher strike price and sell the lower strike price.&nbsp; Lots of Practice!</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1135132251738024_pqX7Pc2Gp1mVnfhvx6tB_height64011.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-17 12:45:43',	'2019-08-17 12:45:43',	''),
(24,	17,	'Stock Option Course',	'<p>A stock option gives a trader and/or investor the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a stock at an agreed upon price and date. There are two types of options: puts, which is a bet that a stock will go down, or calls, which is a bet that a stock will go up. &nbsp;The image above is an option chain. &nbsp;An option chain tells you what is available for each stock if that stock is optionable. &nbsp;If you look at the dates on the left it tells you all the different expiration periods. &nbsp;Stock have either weekly, monthly, quarterly or all the above contracts. &nbsp;In this course we will talk extensively about the important stuff that you need to trade stock options successfully.</p>',	'assets/uploads/users/1135132251738024_pqX7Pc2Gp1mVnfhvx6tB_height64013.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-17 12:49:19',	'2019-08-17 12:49:19',	''),
(33,	17,	'Stock Option Greeks',	'<p>This an image of an opened option chain.&nbsp; When you open the option chain you get a lot of valuable information that you need to make decisions according to your trading system and plan.&nbsp; An option chain gives you volume, open interest, the bid/ask spread, and greeks for both calls and puts.&nbsp; Greeks are delta, gamma, theta and vega which we will talk more about as we go through the course.&nbsp; Depending on your brokerage you can customize your option chain to fit your needs and what information you need to make trading decisions.&nbsp; Generally you want to trade options that have some volume and open interest. The more traders in a particular options strike, the better the chances you&rsquo;ll have to get in and out of your trade without too much slippage.&nbsp; There are many different factors that go into option pricing and how it changes over time according to how the security moves.&nbsp; Delta tells you how much the option will move for every point the security moves.&nbsp; For example if the security move up one point the option would appreciate $0.48 on the 128 calls strike price.&nbsp; Gamma tells you how much the delta will change for every one point move of the security.&nbsp; For example when looking at the 128 calls if the security moves up one point gamma will change delta from $0.48 to $0.57.&nbsp; Theta is time decay so for everyday that passes the option will depreciate whatever amount theta states.&nbsp; All options depreciate regardless if it moves or not.&nbsp; The closer the option gets to expiration date the more it decays or depreciates.&nbsp; That&#39;s why the further out in time you purchase the option the more expensive it will be.&nbsp; For example when looking at the 128 calls everyday that passes the option will depreciate -$0.08.&nbsp; Vega tells us how much an option will change for every percentage move in implied volatility.&nbsp; For example if implied volatility goes up by one percent the 128 calls will increase $0.08.&nbsp; Learning to trade options takes time and practice.&nbsp; There are many different option strategies including spreads and straddles that we will go over.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Option_Chain.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 14:14:33',	'2019-10-27 02:29:14',	''),
(34,	17,	'',	'',	'assets/uploads/users/190_Credit_Spread.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 14:15:29',	'2019-10-27 03:03:30',	''),
(25,	7,	'Green Candlestick',	'<h3>Green Candlestick represents up period in the market.&nbsp; Each candle may have a different length of body and wick depending on open and close of the market.&nbsp; The wick is known as the vertical line at the top and/or bottom of the body.</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/typical_candle_040607_(1).jpg',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-06-29 11:27:33',	'2019-06-29 11:27:33',	''),
(26,	7,	'Green Candlestick',	'<h3>The wick on the top of the candle tells you the high price of that candle which is called upper shadow.&amp;nbsp; The wick on the bottom of the candle tells you the low of that candle which is called the lower shadow.</h3>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Candlestick_Slideshow-625x420-0211.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-20 12:45:24',	'2019-08-20 12:45:24',	''),
(35,	17,	'Stock Option Debit Spread',	'<p>The last vertical spread we talked about was called a credit spread.&nbsp; The vertical spread we will discuss now is called a debit spread.&nbsp; &nbsp; They both can be performed on both calls and puts.&nbsp; One you trade a credit spread you bring in money to your account because the option you bought cost less than the one you sold so you bring the difference into your account.&nbsp; A debit spread money instantly comes out your account because the option you buy will be more expensive than the one you sell.&nbsp; So the debit spread will be inverse to the credit spread.&nbsp; Credit Spreads work best when the market is non-directional a debit spreads work better when the market is moving in a specific direction up or down.&nbsp; By trading a debit spread you put the greeks more in your favor in particular theta which is time decay.&nbsp; For example the image above is a call option chain.&nbsp; If you buy the 215 call for $3.35 and sell the 220 call for $1.90 you will pay $1.45.&nbsp; You ideally want the stock to move above the 220 stock price.&nbsp; As the market rises your spread will balloon in price and you would sell it for a profit.&nbsp; Again the reason why you would buy the spread instead of just buying a single call because the spread protects you from time decay which makes your option lose value every day that you&#39;re in it regardless of if that stock moves up or down.&nbsp; &nbsp;As you get more practice you will get more familiar and will better understand how time and movement effect each option strategy.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/AAPL_Call_Option_Chain.PNG',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-08-24 10:37:57',	'2019-10-27 02:17:42',	''),
(36,	17,	'Stock Option Iron Condor',	'<p>Stock Option Course.&nbsp; The 2 images above is an option chain of a stock and an iron condor option order of that stock.&nbsp; The Iron Condor is an option trading strategy utilizing two vertical&nbsp; credit spreads &ndash; a put spread and a call spread with the same expiration and four different strikes. A long iron condor is essentially selling both sides of the underlying instrument by simultaneously shorting the same number of calls and puts, then covering each position with the purchase of further out of the money call(s) and put(s) respectively.&nbsp; The difference between the put contract strikes will generally be the same as the distance between the call contract strikes.&nbsp; Iron Condor is essentially a delta neutral position so you want there to be no to little volatility on the underline security.&nbsp; In other words you want the stock to move sideways or very slowly.&nbsp; For example for the option chain above you would sell the 115 call, buy the 120 call, sell the 90 put and buy the 85 put.&nbsp; The expiration is in 29 days and you would bring in $0.75 x 100 for each contract because every option contract controls 100 shares of stock so you would essentially make $75 for each contract.&nbsp; As long as the market closes between $115 and $90 by expiration which is the third Friday of the month you will keep the full credit that you made.&nbsp; It takes practice to analyze the market, be able to understand that there is low volatility and trade iron condors effectively.&nbsp; Practice! Practice! Practice!</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Iron_Condor_WING_Ticker.PNG',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-09-07 12:23:57',	'2019-10-27 02:16:44',	''),
(37,	18,	'Trading Psychology Course',	'<p>Trading Psychology Course.&nbsp; The market reflects the actions of its participants and those actions are influenced by what everyone is thinking. As you engage the markets, you will discover things about yourself that may be surprising.&nbsp; One of the main keys of successful trading is identifying those tendencies, attitudes, and behaviors undermining your trading objectives. There is usually a gap between how we actually do things and how we think we do them. In order to make any changes, you need to measure this gap and then derive a plan to close it. This process begins with a realistic assessment of where your trading is right now.The least talked about thing in trading is the most important thing in trading and that is Psychology.&nbsp; Even though you may know when you want to enter and when you want to exit doing it under pressure is very difficult.&nbsp; The reason why there so much pressure is because you have to make split decisions, constantly with real money involved.&nbsp; The holy grail or most important skill a trader can possess is trading without emotion.&nbsp; In trading and life, some things work and others don&#39;t. Trading psychology is about taking inventory of both and making adjustments to improve not only your performance, but also to enhance your experience along the way. The primary objective of trading psychology is to help you stick to your plan. It is hard to reach your destination without it. It is said that &lsquo;luck is when opportunity meets preparation&rsquo;. Trading psychology helps the mind prepare to meet both the market&rsquo;s opportunities and its risks.&nbsp; At Relentless trade we focus more on psychology than we do strategy because knowing what to do is one thing and having the discipline to do it is totally different.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1137084142477951_9HrMmZFvbl3V9m4O4qYP_height6401.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-09-07 12:26:01',	'2019-09-07 12:26:01',	''),
(38,	19,	'Day Trading Course',	'<p>Day Trading Course.&nbsp; Day Trading is one of the hardest ways to make money in the stock market.&nbsp; To Day Trade means you are buying and selling all in the same day never carrying a position overnight.&nbsp; Learning to successful day trade takes a lot of practice.&nbsp; There are may different strategies that you can employ trading intra day but we will talk about some of the most successful strategies we use that includes learning about level II, time and sales which few professionals talk about.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/1140639321177234_5pi73gZKCgTUgfv6lzeY_height6401.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-09-19 13:50:59',	'2019-09-19 13:50:59',	''),
(39,	17,	'Stock Option Straddle',	'<p>Stock Option Course. The straddle option is a neutral strategy in which you simultaneously buy a call option and a put option on the same underlying stock with the same expiration date and strike price. As long as the underlying stock moves sharply enough, then your profit is potentially unlimited. You want to use a straddle option when you suspect there will be a lot of volatility to enter the market or you suspect a really sharp move in either direction up or down. For example if you buy the 127 call strike and the 127 put strike you will pay about $3.59. You will essentially need the stock to move either above the 131 strike or below the 123 strike in a sufficient amount of time before you start to make money. The max you can lose is $3.59.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Option_Chain-1.PNG',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-09-28 12:35:20',	'2019-10-27 02:16:56',	''),
(40,	17,	'Stock Option Strangle',	'<p>Stock Option Course. The option we talked about was a straddle. Now we will discuss a similar strategy known as a strangle. A strangle is a neutral strategy in options trading that involve the simultaneous buying of a slightly out-of-the-money put and a slightly out-of-the-money call of the same underlying stock and expiration date. It is also just like the straddle used for times that you believe there will be significant volatility to come into the market. If you wanna protect yourself for volatility in both direction but give yourself more profit potential in one direction rather than the other you should be trading a strangle. For example if you buy the 128 call strike and buy the 125 put strike you will pay $2.43 which is less than the straddle but you have a better chance of making money if the stock moves up rather than down because of the higher delta. You will still give yourself profit potential on the downside though just not as much as the upside. The put that you buy will cost less than the call that you buy in this trade. If you have a downside bias you would do the inverse have a further out of the money call option than put option.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Option_Chain-3.PNG',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-09-28 12:36:02',	'2019-10-27 02:17:19',	''),
(56,	23,	'Download Trading File ',	'<p>Trading Plan. Most peoples trading plan if they even have one is complex but your trading plan should be very simple and straight forward. The main point of a trading plan is to keep you calm and relaxed during a trade, as all thinking should have been done prior to your entry &ndash; not during your trade. Professional traders are relaxed and composed when trading. Amateurs are nervous before the trade and reckless during the trade. Once your trading plan is complete, you&rsquo;ll find that trading will become more objective, you will be less emotional, and your trades will be more selective. It will add structure and organization to each trading session. It will be your ally when dealing with unexpected moves in the market, rather than making unjustified decisions when a trade does not go as expected. As the trading adage goes &ldquo;Plan Your Trade and Trade Your Plan.&rdquo;</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Download_Files_4_You_Logo.png',	'assets/uploads/video/Why_Im_so_good_at_coding.mp4',	'2019-10-24 06:04:10',	'2019-10-24 09:42:24',	'assets/uploads/video/RelentlessTradesTradingPlan1.docx'),
(64,	17,	'Long Call',	'<p>Stock Option Course.&nbsp; A long call gives you the right to buy the underlying stock at a given strike.&nbsp; If you think a stock is going higher instead of buying the stock outright you can just by a call at a much cheaper price but the option has many more factors as it pertains to profitability than a traditional stock.&nbsp; When you buy a call option you can buy a in the money option (ITM), at the money option (ATM), or out of the money option (OTM).&nbsp; An in the money option has what is known as intrinsic value.&nbsp; This means the stock is higher than the strike price.&nbsp; An at the money strike is the first out of the money strike closest to where the stock is currently trading.&nbsp; An out of the money option has what is known as extrinsic value.&nbsp; This means the stock price is lower than the strike price.&nbsp; To keep things simple when buying a call you always want to give yourself enough time for the stock to perform how you expect.&nbsp; This means you at least want to be 30 to 50 days out as it pertains to expiration because theta which is time decay will tell you how much your option will lose each day regardless if the stock moves or not.&nbsp; Delta and vega is also important but with all things consistent the best option to buy is the one at the money.&nbsp; This will give you the best combination of delta, gamma, theta and vega.&nbsp; With the example above we have bought the 250 strike at 55 days out.&nbsp; Ideally we would like to sell within the next 27 days. As the stock starts to go higher the option will increase in value.&nbsp; Always have a price to sell the option in case the stock starts to go in the opposite direction.&nbsp; When the option gets past the halfway mark of expiration the option value will start to decrease at a faster rate.&nbsp; This means you will lose money faster.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Long_Call.PNG',	'',	'2019-11-02 11:16:44',	'2019-11-02 11:16:44',	''),
(65,	17,	'Long Put',	'<p>Stock Option Course.&nbsp; A long put gives you the right to sell the underlying stock at a given strike.&nbsp; If you think a stock is going lower instead of shorting the stock outright you can just by a put at a much cheaper price but the option has many more factors as it pertains to profitability than a traditional stock.&nbsp; When you buy a put option you can buy a in the money option (ITM), at the money option (ATM), or out of the money option (OTM).&nbsp; An in the money option has what is known as intrinsic value.&nbsp; This means the stock is lower than the strike price.&nbsp; An at the money strike is the first out of the money strike closest to where the stock is currently trading.&nbsp; An out of the money option has what is known as extrinsic value.&nbsp; This means the stock price is higher than the strike price.&nbsp; To keep things simple when buying a put you always want to give yourself enough time for the stock to perform how you expect.&nbsp; This means you at least want to be 30 to 50 days out as it pertains to expiration because theta which is time decay will tell you how much your option will lose each day regardless if the stock moves or not.&nbsp; Delta and vega is also important but with all things consistent the best option to buy is the one at the money.&nbsp; This will give you the best combination of delta, gamma, theta and vega.&nbsp; With the example above we have bought the 245 strike at 55 days out.&nbsp; Ideally we would like to sell within the next 27 days.&nbsp; As the stock starts to go lower the option will increase in value.&nbsp; Always have a&nbsp; price to sell the option in case the stock starts to go in the opposite direction. When the option time gets past the halfway mark of expiration the option value will start to decrease at a faster rate.&nbsp; This means you will lose money faster.</p>\r\n',	'assets/uploads/users/Long_Put.PNG',	'',	'2019-11-02 11:17:31',	'2019-11-02 11:17:31',	''),
